knowledge_graph.title: Macadamia
knowledge_graph.description: Macadamia is a genus of four species of trees in the flowering plant family Proteaceae. They are indigenous to Australia, native to northeastern New South Wales and central and southeastern Queensland specifically. Two species of the genus are commercially important for their fruit, the macadamia nut.

related_questions.question: Is eating macadamia nuts good for you?
related_questions.snippet: Macadamia nuts are naturally low in sugar and carbohydrates. They also contain various essential nutrients such as dietary fiber and antioxidants that help reduce the risk or manage conditions such as cardiovascular disease, diabetes, and digestive health. They're also an excellent source of: Protein.

related_questions.question: Who should not eat macadamia nuts?
related_questions.snippet: Those with nut allergies need to avoid macadamia nuts completely. Those who live with a person who has nut allergies may also wish to steer clear of them. This is due to the risk of cross-contamination or accidentally exposing them to trace amounts of nuts.

related_questions.question: Why is macadamia so expensive?
related_questions.snippet: Scarcely Farmed – only 1% of tree nuts produced worldwide are macadamia! One of the main reasons that macadamia nuts are expensive is because of their supply. Like most tree nuts, macadamia grow on trees, and this leads to a delay from planting to harvest.

related_questions.question: How many macadamia nuts can I eat a day?
related_questions.snippet: How many macadamias is it healthy to eat? A healthy handful of macadamias is about 30g or 15 whole nuts. We should all strive to eat at least one healthy handful per day. But there's no reason why you can't eat more.
